eduled to set up the first working group on cooperation in the Asia Pacific region to address potential threats ranging from non-traditional militaries to countries that are “compliant with Australia’s obligations of international law,” Bishop said. Australia will take part in the meetings, which will also include those from the United States and several others, Bishop said. “Australia welcomes this work and will work to support the efforts of the regional security team to bring about an agreement which we want to achieve to be a positive and safe time for Australian businesses to collaborate with our friends and allies and partner members of the international community to ensure this successful and effective agreement to be reviewed,” she added. Australia has worked aggressively with some governments in the region, notably Washington, to strengthen bilateral cyber-security cooperation, including on cyber security cooperation for the United States and the ability to share information without being hacked, but the Australian foreign ministry said it had been unable to negotiate a final deal. Japan’s defense ministry said it would issue a statement on the planned working group after the Australian foreign ministry finalised a statement on the status of the agreement. Australian Foreign Minister Julie Bishop said Japan and Australia had agreed a mutual commitment that the defense force to be responsible for managing “the security
